FLASHCARDS.push(
  // g10i-03-1 — River Processes
  {id:"g10fc-03-1-1", islandId:"g10i-03-1", front:"Describe the four processes of river erosion.",
   back:"1. Hydraulic action — the force of water hitting the river bed and banks, compressing air into cracks and weakening the rock.\n\n2. Abrasion — rocks and pebbles carried by the river scrape and wear away the bed and banks (like sandpaper).\n\n3. Attrition — rocks and pebbles carried by the river collide with each other, becoming smaller and rounder over time.\n\n4. Solution (corrosion) — slightly acidic river water dissolves soluble rocks such as chalk and limestone.\n\nHydraulic action and abrasion are the most powerful erosion processes, especially during high-discharge flood events.", difficulty:2, category:"concept"},
  {id:"g10fc-03-1-2", islandId:"g10i-03-1", front:"Explain the four methods of river transportation.",
   back:"Rivers transport material (the load) downstream using four methods:\n\n1. Traction — large boulders and rocks are rolled along the river bed by the force of the water.\n\n2. Saltation — smaller pebbles and gravel are bounced along the bed in a hopping motion.\n\n3. Suspension — fine particles of silt and clay are carried within the water, giving it a muddy appearance.\n\n4. Solution — dissolved minerals are carried invisibly within the water.\n\nThe method used depends on the size of the material and the velocity of the river. During floods, even large boulders can be transported.", difficulty:2, category:"concept"},
  {id:"g10fc-03-1-3", islandId:"g10i-03-1", front:"When and where does a river deposit material?",
   back:"Deposition occurs when a river loses energy and can no longer carry its load.\n\nConditions that cause deposition:\n• Reduced velocity — when the river enters a lake or the sea, or the gradient decreases\n• Reduced discharge — during dry periods when there is less water\n• Inside of a meander — water flows more slowly on the inside bend\n• When a river floods — water spreads onto the floodplain, slows down and drops sediment\n• Obstructions — boulders or vegetation slow the flow\n\nLarger, heavier particles are deposited first; fine silt and clay settle last. This sorting of sediment is called graded bedding.", difficulty:2, category:"concept"},
  {id:"g10fc-03-1-4", islandId:"g10i-03-1", front:"How does a river's cross-profile change from source to mouth?",
   back:"Upper course (near source):\n• Narrow and shallow channel\n• V-shaped valley with steep sides\n• Large angular boulders on the bed\n• Vertical erosion dominates\n\nMiddle course:\n• Wider, deeper channel\n• Valley begins to flatten\n• Load becomes smaller and rounder (attrition)\n• Lateral (sideways) erosion begins\n\nLower course (near mouth):\n• Very wide, deep channel\n• Flat, wide floodplain\n• Fine sediment (silt, clay)\n• Deposition dominates; lateral erosion continues\n\nDischarge increases downstream as tributaries join. Velocity also generally increases because, despite a gentler gradient, the larger channel has less friction per unit of water.", difficulty:2, category:"concept"},
  {id:"g10fc-03-1-5", islandId:"g10i-03-1", front:"What is the Bradshaw Model and what does it show?",
   back:"The Bradshaw Model describes how river characteristics change from source to mouth:\n\nIncreases downstream:\n• Discharge — more tributaries join\n• Velocity — larger channel means less friction relative to volume\n• Channel width and depth\n• Load quantity — more material transported\n\nDecreases downstream:\n• Channel bed roughness — bed becomes smoother\n• Load particle size — attrition reduces particles\n• Gradient — slope decreases\n\nThe model is a generalisation — local factors (geology, confluences, human management) can create variations. It is a useful framework for understanding the overall pattern of river behaviour.", difficulty:2, category:"application"},

  // g10i-03-2 — River Landforms
  {id:"g10fc-03-2-1", islandId:"g10i-03-2", front:"Explain the formation of a V-shaped valley and interlocking spurs.",
   back:"In the upper course, the river has a steep gradient and erodes primarily downward (vertical erosion).\n\n1. Hydraulic action and abrasion deepen the river channel.\n2. The steep valley sides are exposed to weathering (freeze-thaw, chemical) and mass movement (soil creep, slumping).\n3. Weathered material falls into the river and is transported downstream.\n4. The result is a steep-sided, V-shaped valley.\n\nInterlocking spurs form because the river does not have enough energy to erode laterally. It winds around ridges of hard rock, creating a zigzag pattern where spurs from alternate sides interlock like the teeth of a zip.", difficulty:2, category:"process"},
  {id:"g10fc-03-2-2", islandId:"g10i-03-2", front:"Explain the formation of a waterfall and gorge.",
   back:"Waterfalls form where a river crosses a band of hard rock overlying softer rock:\n\n1. The river erodes the softer rock downstream more quickly than the hard rock.\n2. A step or ledge develops where the hard rock is left overhanging.\n3. Water plunges over the ledge, and hydraulic action and abrasion erode a deep plunge pool at the base.\n4. The softer rock beneath the hard cap is undercut, creating an overhang.\n5. Over time, the unsupported overhang collapses.\n6. This process repeats, and the waterfall retreats upstream.\n7. The retreat leaves behind a steep-sided gorge.\n\nExample: High Force waterfall on the River Tees (hard Whin Sill dolerite over softer limestone and shale).", difficulty:2, category:"process"},
  {id:"g10fc-03-2-3", islandId:"g10i-03-2", front:"Explain the formation of meanders and oxbow lakes.",
   back:"Meanders:\n1. In the middle and lower course, the river begins to erode laterally.\n2. On the outside of a bend, water flows faster (deeper, less friction) and erodes the bank by hydraulic action and abrasion, creating a river cliff.\n3. On the inside of the bend, water flows slowly and deposits material, forming a slip-off slope (point bar).\n4. Over time, the meander migrates laterally and downstream.\n\nOxbow lakes:\n1. Continued erosion on the outer bends brings the two outer banks of a meander loop closer together.\n2. During a flood, the river breaks through the narrow neck of land, taking the shorter, straighter route.\n3. Deposition seals off the old meander loop.\n4. The cut-off loop becomes an oxbow lake, which gradually silts up and may become a marsh.", difficulty:2, category:"process"},
  {id:"g10fc-03-2-4", islandId:"g10i-03-2", front:"How are floodplains and levees formed?",
   back:"Floodplains:\n• When a river floods, water spreads over the flat valley floor.\n• As water spreads out, velocity decreases and sediment (alluvium) is deposited.\n• Repeated flooding builds up layers of fertile alluvium, creating the flat floodplain.\n• Meander migration also widens the floodplain as the river erodes laterally.\n\nLevees:\n• During a flood, the heaviest, coarsest sediment is deposited first, closest to the river channel (where velocity drops most sharply as water leaves the channel).\n• Finer material is deposited further from the channel on the floodplain.\n• Over many floods, the coarse deposits build up into raised banks called levees on either side of the river.\n\nExample: the Mississippi River has extensive natural levees.", difficulty:2, category:"process"},
  {id:"g10fc-03-2-5", islandId:"g10i-03-2", front:"What is an estuary and how does it form?",
   back:"An estuary is the tidal mouth of a river where freshwater meets saltwater from the sea.\n\nFormation:\n• At the mouth of the river, the channel widens significantly.\n• The river's velocity decreases as it meets the sea, causing extensive deposition of fine sediment (silt, mud).\n• Tidal movements carry saltwater upstream and flush sediment back and forth.\n• Mudflats and saltmarshes may develop on deposited material.\n\nCharacteristics:\n• Brackish water (mix of fresh and salt)\n• Rich in nutrients — important habitats for birds, fish and invertebrates\n• Often sites of major ports and cities (e.g. London on the Thames estuary)\n• Subject to tidal flooding and storm surge risk", difficulty:2, category:"concept"},

  // g10i-03-3 — Flooding & Management
  {id:"g10fc-03-3-1", islandId:"g10i-03-3", front:"Explain the physical and human causes of river flooding.",
   back:"Physical causes:\n• Prolonged, heavy rainfall saturates the ground, increasing surface runoff\n• Snowmelt — rapid thaw adds large volumes of water\n• Steep slopes — water reaches the river quickly\n• Impermeable rock — water cannot infiltrate, so it runs off the surface\n• Saturated soil — no more water can be absorbed\n\nHuman causes:\n• Urbanisation — concrete and tarmac are impermeable, increasing surface runoff\n• Deforestation — fewer trees to intercept rainfall and absorb water through roots\n• Agriculture — ploughing compacts soil, reducing infiltration\n• Draining wetlands — removes natural water storage areas\n• River straightening — water reaches downstream areas faster\n\nFlooding usually results from a combination of physical and human factors.", difficulty:2, category:"concept"},
  {id:"g10fc-03-3-2", islandId:"g10i-03-3", front:"How do you interpret a storm hydrograph?",
   back:"A storm hydrograph shows how a river's discharge changes over time after a rainfall event.\n\nKey features:\n• Rainfall bars — show the intensity and duration of rainfall\n• Rising limb — the increase in discharge as water reaches the river\n• Peak discharge — the highest point; the maximum flow\n• Lag time — the delay between peak rainfall and peak discharge\n• Falling limb — the decrease in discharge as water drains through\n• Base flow — the normal level of the river fed by groundwater\n\nA short lag time and steep rising limb indicate a 'flashy' hydrograph — high flood risk.\nA long lag time and gentle rising limb indicate a 'flat' hydrograph — low flood risk.\n\nFactors reducing lag time: impermeable rock, steep slopes, urbanisation, deforestation.", difficulty:2, category:"application"},
  {id:"g10fc-03-3-3", islandId:"g10i-03-3", front:"Describe a UK flood event case study.",
   back:"Case study: Boscastle, Cornwall — 16 August 2004\n\nCauses:\n• 89 mm of rain fell in one hour (a month's rainfall in 60 minutes)\n• Steep-sided valley funnelled water rapidly into the River Valency\n• Saturated ground from previous days of rain\n• Narrow river channel through the village\n\nEffects:\n• Over 100 cars swept out to sea\n• 58 properties flooded; some destroyed\n• No deaths (due to helicopter rescue)\n• Roads and bridges destroyed\n• Tourism and local businesses severely disrupted\n\nResponse:\n• Immediate: RAF helicopter rescue of 100+ people\n• Long-term: river channel widened; higher bridges built; flood defences improved; land management upstream enhanced", difficulty:2, category:"case-study"},
  {id:"g10fc-03-3-4", islandId:"g10i-03-3", front:"Compare hard and soft engineering flood management strategies.",
   back:"Hard engineering (artificial structures):\n• Dams and reservoirs — control flow; store water; expensive; displace communities\n• Embankments (levees) — raise river banks; protect land behind; can give false sense of security\n• Channel straightening — speeds flow past settlements; increases flood risk downstream\n• Flood walls — protect specific areas; visually intrusive; expensive\n\nSoft engineering (working with nature):\n• Floodplain zoning — restricts building on floodplains; no cost to build but limits development\n• Afforestation — planting trees to intercept rainfall and slow runoff; cheap but takes years\n• Managed flooding (washlands) — allowing deliberate flooding of low-value land\n• River restoration — re-meandering straightened rivers to slow flow\n\nSoft engineering is generally cheaper, more sustainable and more environmentally friendly, but hard engineering provides more immediate protection.", difficulty:2, category:"evaluation"},
  {id:"g10fc-03-3-5", islandId:"g10i-03-3", front:"Evaluate whether hard or soft engineering is better for managing river flooding.",
   back:"Hard engineering:\n+ Provides immediate, physical protection\n+ Dams can also generate hydroelectric power and supply water\n+ Effective for protecting high-value urban areas\n− Very expensive to build and maintain\n− Can increase flood risk elsewhere (e.g. straightening speeds water downstream)\n− Environmentally damaging; may displace communities\n\nSoft engineering:\n+ Works with natural processes; more sustainable long-term\n+ Cheaper to implement and maintain\n+ Creates habitats and improves water quality\n− Takes longer to have an effect (e.g. tree planting)\n− May not provide sufficient protection for major urban areas\n− Requires ongoing commitment and public education\n\nConclusion: the best approach combines both strategies — hard engineering to protect key areas and soft engineering to manage the wider catchment. This integrated approach is increasingly favoured by the Environment Agency.", difficulty:3, category:"evaluation"},

  // g10i-03-4 — Erosional River Landforms
  {id:"g10fc-03-4-1", islandId:"g10i-03-4", front:"Name the four processes of river erosion and the four methods of transport.",
   back:"Erosion (four processes):\n1. Hydraulic action — the force of water forces air into cracks, weakening the bed and banks.\n2. Abrasion — the load scrapes against the bed and banks like sandpaper.\n3. Attrition — rocks in the load collide and become smaller and rounder.\n4. Solution (corrosion) — acidic water dissolves soluble rock such as chalk and limestone.\n\nTransport (four methods):\n1. Traction — large boulders are rolled along the bed.\n2. Saltation — pebbles bounce along the bed in a hopping motion.\n3. Suspension — fine silt and clay are carried within the flow.\n4. Solution — dissolved minerals are carried invisibly in the water.\n\nIn the upper course, vertical erosion dominates, deepening the channel.", difficulty:2, category:"concept"},
  {id:"g10fc-03-4-2", islandId:"g10i-03-4", front:"Explain how a V-shaped valley and interlocking spurs form.",
   back:"In the upper course the river has a steep gradient and erodes mainly downwards (vertical erosion).\n\nV-shaped valley:\n1. Hydraulic action and abrasion deepen the channel.\n2. The exposed steep valley sides are attacked by weathering (e.g. freeze-thaw) and mass movement (soil creep, slumping).\n3. Loosened material falls into the river and is transported away.\n4. The result is a narrow, steep-sided, V-shaped valley.\n\nInterlocking spurs:\n• The river lacks the energy to erode laterally, so it winds around bands of more resistant rock (ridges).\n• These ridges, called spurs, project alternately from each side of the valley.\n• Viewed downstream they appear to interlock like the teeth of a zip.", difficulty:2, category:"process"},
  {id:"g10fc-03-4-3", islandId:"g10i-03-4", front:"Explain step by step how a waterfall and gorge form.",
   back:"Waterfalls form where a band of hard rock lies over softer rock:\n1. The softer rock downstream is eroded more quickly than the hard cap rock.\n2. A step or ledge develops, and water plunges over it.\n3. Hydraulic action and abrasion erode a deep plunge pool at the base.\n4. The softer rock beneath the hard cap is undercut, leaving an overhang.\n5. The unsupported overhang eventually collapses into the plunge pool.\n6. The collapsed rock swirls in the plunge pool, deepening it by abrasion.\n7. The process repeats and the waterfall retreats upstream.\n8. The retreat leaves a steep-sided, narrow valley called a gorge.\n\nExample: High Force on the River Tees, where hard Whin Sill dolerite overlies softer limestone and shale.", difficulty:2, category:"process"},
  {id:"g10fc-03-4-4", islandId:"g10i-03-4", front:"Why does vertical erosion dominate in the upper course?",
   back:"In the upper course:\n• The gradient is steep, so the river's energy is directed downwards rather than sideways.\n• The channel is narrow and shallow, with large angular boulders, creating high friction.\n• Most of the river's limited energy is used overcoming this friction and cutting down into the bed.\n• Hydraulic action and abrasion act on the bed, deepening the channel.\n\nThis downward (vertical) cutting produces:\n• A narrow, deep channel\n• Steep valley sides (V-shaped valley)\n• Interlocking spurs where the river winds around resistant ridges\n\nLateral (sideways) erosion only becomes dominant in the middle and lower course, where the gradient gentles and discharge increases.", difficulty:2, category:"concept"},
  {id:"g10fc-03-4-5", islandId:"g10i-03-4", front:"How do transport processes change the load as it moves downstream?",
   back:"As the load is transported from source to mouth, it changes in two key ways:\n\n1. Size decreases — repeated collisions during traction and saltation cause attrition, breaking the load into smaller fragments. By the lower course only fine silt and clay remain, carried in suspension and solution.\n\n2. Shape becomes rounder — attrition knocks off sharp edges, so angular upper-course boulders become smooth, rounded pebbles downstream.\n\nThe dominant transport method also shifts:\n• Upper course — traction and saltation (coarse load, high energy needed)\n• Lower course — suspension and solution (fine load, lower energy)\n\nThis explains the upper-course landforms: the large, angular boulders aid abrasion, deepening the channel and forming V-shaped valleys.", difficulty:2, category:"application"},

  // g10i-03-5 — Depositional River Landforms
  {id:"g10fc-03-5-1", islandId:"g10i-03-5", front:"Why does deposition occur in the lower course of a river?",
   back:"Deposition occurs when a river loses energy and can no longer carry its load.\n\nIn the lower course this happens because:\n• The gradient is very gentle, so velocity falls where the channel shallows or the river meets the sea.\n• Discharge may drop during drier periods, reducing energy.\n• The river meets the still water of a lake or the sea at the mouth.\n• Friction increases on the inside of meander bends, slowing the flow.\n\nThe largest, heaviest particles are deposited first; the finest silt and clay settle last. This sorting produces the fine, fertile alluvium of the floodplain. Deposition builds depositional landforms such as meanders, floodplains, levées and estuaries.", difficulty:2, category:"concept"},
  {id:"g10fc-03-5-2", islandId:"g10i-03-5", front:"Explain how a meander forms, referring to the outer and inner bank.",
   back:"Meanders are sweeping bends in the middle and lower course, where the river erodes laterally.\n\nOuter bank (river cliff):\n• Water flows faster and deeper here because friction is lower.\n• Erosion by hydraulic action and abrasion undercuts the bank.\n• This forms a steep river cliff.\n\nInner bank (slip-off slope):\n• Water flows slowly and is shallow here, so the river loses energy.\n• Sediment is deposited, building a gentle slip-off slope (point bar).\n\nThe combination of erosion on the outer bank and deposition on the inner bank makes the meander migrate sideways and downstream over time, widening the floodplain. Meanders are therefore asymmetrical in cross-section.", difficulty:2, category:"process"},
  {id:"g10fc-03-5-3", islandId:"g10i-03-5", front:"Describe how an oxbow lake forms.",
   back:"An oxbow lake is a crescent-shaped lake left when a meander is cut off:\n\n1. Erosion on the outer banks of a meander loop makes the neck of land between two bends progressively narrower.\n2. Continued erosion brings the two outer banks very close together.\n3. During a flood, the river has enough energy to break straight through the narrow neck, taking the shorter, straighter route.\n4. Deposition then builds up across the entrance to the old loop, sealing it off from the main channel.\n5. The abandoned meander loop becomes an oxbow lake.\n6. Over time the lake silts up, becomes a marsh and may dry out completely, leaving a meander scar.", difficulty:2, category:"process"},
  {id:"g10fc-03-5-4", islandId:"g10i-03-5", front:"How do floodplains and levées form?",
   back:"Floodplains:\n• When a river floods, water spreads across the flat valley floor and loses velocity.\n• Sediment (alluvium) is deposited in layers, building up fertile soil.\n• Lateral erosion from meander migration also widens the floodplain.\n\nLevées (raised natural banks):\n• During a flood, water leaving the channel slows suddenly.\n• The coarsest, heaviest sediment is dropped first, right next to the channel.\n• Finer material is carried further onto the floodplain.\n• After many floods, the coarse deposits build up into raised banks (levées) along both sides of the channel.\n\nLevées can raise the river above the level of its floodplain. Example: the Mississippi River has extensive natural levées.", difficulty:2, category:"process"},
  {id:"g10fc-03-5-5", islandId:"g10i-03-5", front:"What is an estuary and how does it form?",
   back:"An estuary is the tidal mouth of a river, where freshwater meets saltwater.\n\nFormation:\n• At the mouth, the channel widens and the river's velocity falls as it meets the sea.\n• This causes extensive deposition of fine sediment (silt and mud).\n• Tides move water and sediment up and down the channel twice daily.\n• Mudflats are exposed at low tide; over time saltmarshes colonise them.\n\nCharacteristics:\n• Brackish water (mixed fresh and salt)\n• Nutrient-rich — important habitats for wading birds, fish and invertebrates\n• Often sites of major ports and cities (e.g. London on the Thames estuary)\n• Vulnerable to tidal flooding and storm surge.", difficulty:2, category:"concept"}
);

